such changes to have become manifest. Second, despite the improvements
that have occurred, the present low inflation environment cannot
be taken for granted. In particular, to maintain that environment,
policy will have to continue to be forward-looking in responding
to prospective inflation pressures before they can accumulate. Third,
the case for lowering inflation further is strongest for those countries
with fairly flexible labour and product markets. In countries where
considerable rigidities remain, the main priorities are to preserve
