experience of most of these countries with monetary targeting or
a fixed exchange rate had proved unsatisfactory, this new framework
for the conduct of monetary policy was required. In theory, an inflation
target is relatively straightforward. The central bank forecasts
the future path of inflation; the forecast is compared with the target
inflation rate; the difference between the forecast and the target
determines the required adjustment of the monetary policy instrument.
However, the experience to date of the inflation targeting countries
has identified a number of complex operational issues. This paper
highlights five aspects of the inflation targeting framework: the
assignment of the target, the interaction with other policy goals,
